    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lure the Best to a Life of Teaching</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rose Beth Mandelbaum letter on Harold O Levy's Sept 9 article notes teachers are not rewarded for superior job performance</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Why the Best Don't Teach,'' by Harold O. Levy (Op-Ed, Sept. 9):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Why the Best Don't Teach,'' by Harold O. Levy (Op-Ed, Sept. 9):</p>
        <p>I taught high school math in the mid-1970's and left after five years for a variety of reasons, some of them discussed by Mr. Levy. I was also motivated by an additional factor: the realization that my job performance would never have any bearing on my salary.</p>
        <p>Teachers' salaries are determined by a formula combining years of service with degrees or credits earned. How good a job one is doing appears nowhere on the matrix.</p>
        <p>Although talented college students may be willing to become teachers knowing that they will not get rich, it is unrealistic to expect the brightest and most creative to enter a field in which superior performance and extra effort will never be reflected in their paychecks.</p>
        <p>ROSE BETH MANDELBAUM  Brookline, Mass., Sept. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
